This paper is about using neural networks to generate replies in human-computer dialogue systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). The paper specifically focuses on improving the content of the generated replies, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the use of pointwise mutual information (PMI) and sequence-to-sequence models are common techniques in NLP and machine learning, which could also place this paper in the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), machine learning (cs.LG), information retrieval (cs.IR), and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE).
